article.description:
Larry Brown's halftime criticism motivated Allen
Iverson.
article.headline: Iverson scores 18 of 32 points in second half
article.linkText: Brown inspires Iverson, 76ers in rout of Raptors
article.story:
TORONTO (AP) --Larry Brown's halftime criticism motivated Allen Iverson.
Iverson

Iverson stepped up his defensive intensity and scored 18 of his 32 points in the second half as the Philadelphia 76ers ended a two-game losing streak with a 112-95 victory over the Toronto Raptors on Sunday. The Sixers struggled in the first half, allowing Toronto to shot 55 percent from the field and take a 58-55 lead at halftime, leading to Brown's locker room speech. "He got on me pretty bad,'' Iverson said. "He got on a lot of other guys as well. The good thing about that is that we didn't take it personal.'' Iverson, the league's No. 3 scorer, recovered from two subpar games -- he had just five points in Thursday's loss to Detroit and went 9-for-27 from the field in Saturday's loss to Atlanta -- to go 14-for-25 from the field. He added seven assists and five steals. "I feel a lot better about my game. I've been searching for it,'' Iverson said. "Hopefully, I found it. I just played well today.'' Vince Carter had 22 points on 10-for-13 shooting for the lottery-bound Raptors, who have lost eight of nine. Iverson had 14 points during the third quarter when Philadelphia outscored Toronto 31-19. "We really responded. Allen dived for loose balls and guys made hustle plays,'' Brown said. Toronto's Alvin Williams made a layup to tie it at 71 with 5:44 left in the third before the Sixers went on a 15-6 run. Iverson, who had six points and two assists during the run, hit a jumper that gave the Sixers a nine-point lead just before the end of the quarter. The Sixers maintained control in the fourth and when Iverson made a layup midway through the quarter their lead was 14, 96-82. "I got into a rhythm and after a while the basket started looking like an ocean,'' Iverson said. Eric Snow added 11 points and 11 assists for the Sixers, who are 16-4 since the All-Star break. Philadelphia shot 56.4 percent from the field. "We had good emotion but we can't allow ourselves to get beat that easily,'' Toronto coach Lenny Wilkens said. Carter had 11 points and Voshon Lenard had 10 at halftime. Game notes
Raptors forward Jerome Williams missed the game with a sprained neck. Williams missed two games earlier this month with the injury. ... Carter and Philadelphia's Tyrone Hill had to be separated from each other late in the fourth when Hill took exception to Carter fouling Greg Buckner. ... Toronto's Michael Bradley had 10 points and eight rebounds in his first start of the season. ... Center Antonio Davis returned to the lineup after missing a game with a bruised right knee. Davis had 10 points and nine rebounds. ... Philadelphia's Derrick Coleman received six stitches over his left eye after being cut in the first half. ... Actor Jaleel White -- who played the nerdy, bespectacled Steve Urkel in the '90s sitcom "Family Matters'' -- sat courtside.
